          "body": "Psalm 23 does not stand alone. It is the middle psalm of a deliberate triad: Psalm 22 is the suffering Messiah's lament ('My God, My God, why have You forsaken Me?' — quoted by Christ on the cross, Matthew 27:46), and Psalm 24 is the King of Glory's victorious entry ('Lift up your heads, O gates'). Between cross (Ps 22) and crown (Ps 24) sits the Shepherd's care of His own (Ps 23). The canonical placement is not accidental. The same Christ who suffered the wrath of forsakenness in Psalm 22 and who returns as the King of Glory in Psalm 24 is the Good Shepherd of Psalm 23 (John 10:11), and the table He prepares is fulfilled in the Lord's Supper, and the house He brings the sheep into is fulfilled in the New Jerusalem. The psalm is Davidic in origin, Christological in fulfillment, and personal in application."
