        "number": 6,
        "title": "Canonical fulfillment — the Shepherd of John 10 and the table of the Lord",
        "range": "23:1-6",
        "excerpt": "I am the good shepherd; the good shepherd lays down His life for the sheep. (John 10:11)",
        "body": "Psalm 23 does not stay in David's mouth. The New Testament picks up every metaphor and locates it in Christ.\n\nThe **shepherd** of Psalm 23:1 becomes the *Good Shepherd* of John 10:11 — the same Greek word *poimēn* the LXX uses for *ro'i*. And what David could only confess (*Yahweh is my shepherd*), Christ embodies (*I am the good shepherd*). The 'I am' is the same *egō eimi* that translates *Yahweh* — the Shepherd of Psalm 23 stands in the flesh in John 10 and identifies Himself with the covenant name. The metaphor and the Person merge.\n\nThe **valley of the shadow of death** of Psalm 23:4 is the same *skia thanatou* into which the Light shines at Matthew 4:16 and Luke 1:79 (both quoting Isaiah 9:2 via the LXX). The Christ who walks through Galilee is the dayspring that pierces the shadow David walked through. And the Good Shepherd does more than walk *through* the valley — He *enters* it as substitute. *The good shepherd lays down His life for the sheep* (John 10:11). The Shepherd of Psalm 23 becomes the Lamb of John 1:29; the One who carried rod and staff bears the cross.\n\nThe **table** of Psalm 23:5 finds its supreme fulfillment in the table Christ sets the night before His death (Luke 22:19-20) and the table believers eat at every Lord's Supper (1 Corinthians 11:23-26). The host who anoints the head with oil is the Christ whose feet are anointed at Bethany (John 12:3). The cup that overflows in Psalm 23 is the *cup of blessing* (1 Corinthians 10:16). And the table is eaten *in the presence of* the enemies still — the world's hostility has not ended; the meal proceeds anyway.\n\nThe **house of the LORD** of Psalm 23:6 reaches its eschatological terminus at Revelation 21:3, where *the tabernacle of God is among men, and He shall dwell among them, and they shall be His people, and God Himself shall be among them.* The *bet-Yahweh* of David's day was a tent on Zion; the *bet-Yahweh* of the new creation is the Lamb Himself, for John writes that *the Lord God the Almighty and the Lamb are the temple* of the New Jerusalem (Revelation 21:22). The dwelling is no longer a building; the dwelling *is* the Shepherd. David could not see this far, but the canon does.\n\nThe psalm's **placement** in the Psalter ratifies the reading. Psalm 22 is the suffering Messiah's lament, quoted by Christ on the cross (Matthew 27:46). Psalm 24 is the King of Glory's victorious entry. Between the cross and the crown sits Psalm 23 — the Good Shepherd's care of those for whom He died and over whom He reigns. The triad reads as one canonical sentence: He suffered (Ps 22), He shepherds (Ps 23), He reigns (Ps 24). And the One who suffered, shepherds, and reigns is the same Christ from beginning to end."
